Thanks for working on this, [~bharatviswa].

Looks good to me overall, just few minor comments:
 # We can directly assign the default policy to {{ecPolicyName}} and not need another variable {{ecName}}.
 # We would not need the below if condition as ecPolicyName cannot be null anymore.

{code:java}
if (ecPolicyName == null){
  System.out.println("Set default erasure coding policy " + ecName
      + " on " + path);
} {code}

Hi [~xiaochen]

As we are reading the value available from the config in ECAdmin, and we are passing the same to dfs.setErasureCodingPolicy(p, ecPolicyName);

That is the value we are printing as default. So, what is the default policy set in the client(where command is invoked), that is the default policy with which ecPolicy will be set for the path.

If you look into the code, null is handled at:
{code:java title= NameNodeRpcServer}
public void setErasureCodingPolicy(String src, String ecPolicyName)
throws IOException {
...
if (ecPolicyName == null) {
ecPolicyName = defaultECPolicyName;
LOG.trace("No policy name is specified, " +
"set the default policy name instead");
}
LOG.trace("Set erasure coding policy " + ecPolicyName + " on " + src);
namesystem.setErasureCodingPolicy(src, ecPolicyName, cacheEntry != null);
...{code}
which is on NN, no?

Hi [~xiaochen]

If you see the updated code in the patch (ECAdmin.java), we are setting ecPolicyName if the user does not pass any value.

So, we will not pass a null value.
{code:java}
if (ecPolicyName == null) {
ecPolicyName = conf.get(DFSConfigKeys
.DFS_NAMENODE_EC_SYSTEM_DEFAULT_POLICY, DFSConfigKeys
.DFS_NAMENODE_EC_SYSTEM_DEFAULT_POLICY_DEFAULT);
isDefaultPolicy = true;
}

final Path p = new Path(path);
final DistributedFileSystem dfs = AdminHelper.getDFS(p.toUri(), conf);
try {
dfs.setErasureCodingPolicy(p, ecPolicyName);{code}
